<h2>Conquer Fansipan Mountain</h2>
<p>Fansipan (also written as Phan Si Pang , Phan Xi Pang or Phan Si Pang, Phan Si Pang ) is Vietnam 's highest mountain peak , located on the Hoang Lien Son mountain range in the Northwest region of Vietnam. The mountain peak has an absolute height of 3147.3 m. Fansipan is also the highest mountain peak in the Indochina peninsula and is known as the "Roof of Indochina"</p>
<h3 class="mountaintitle">Etymology</h3>
<p>The origin of the word Fanxipan is unclear. Many sources believe that Fansipan peak has another name, Hua Xi Pan and confirm that this name is of Mandarin origin, meaning "unstable giant rock". Another theory is that the name is Hmong, meaning Rhododendron Mountain because of the popularity of rhododendrons and plants. belongs to the genus Rhododendron in the mountains. There is also an opinion that this name is the pronunciation of Phan Van Son, the name of a Nguyen Dynasty geographer, who in 1905 together with the French drew a map and demarcated the border between Vietnam and the Dynasty. Bar.</p>
<img class="img6" src="{{asset('blog/files/fansipan1.jpg')}}" alt="nÃºi fansipan">
<h3 class="mountaintitle">Geography</h3>
<p>Fansipan is the highest peak in the Hoang Lien Son mountain range , located on the border of Lao Cai province and Lai Chau province. Administratively, Fansipan peak belongs to the boundaries of both Tam Duong district ( Lai Chau ) and Sa Pa town ( Lao Cai ), about 9 km southwest of Sa Pa town center. The height of the mountain peak measured in 1909 is 3143 m, however, according to the latest data released by the Vietnam Department of Surveying, Mapping and Geographic Information at the end of June 2019, the mountain peak is 3147.3 meters high. m.</p><br>
<p>This is also the highest point of the three Indochina countries ( Vietnam , Laos , Cambodia ), so Fansipan is also known as the " Roof of Indochina ".</p>
<h3 class="mountaintitle">History of geological tectonics</h3>
<p>Fansipan was formed during the transition period of the Permian and Triassic periods of the Paleozoic and Mesozoic Era, 260-250 million years ago. The Himalayas, since the late Mesozoic, have raised the Fansipan peak and the Hoang Lien Son range, and created the Red River fault to the east.</p>
